Wherever water flows, it almost always carries sedimentâparticles of sand, silt or clay that flow, scour, accumulate and disperse to help form and reform Earthâs features over time. Sediment helps to create natural habitats and to alter geography, and an understanding of its complex processes is key to many planning and conservation decisions.

[caption id="attachment_188371" align="alignright" width="368"]<a href="http://www.usgs.gov/blogs/features/files/2014/01/20071026-TER-52.jpg"><img class="wp-image-188371 " title="20071026-TER-52" src="http://www.usgs.gov/blogs/features/files/2014/01/20071026-TER-52-1024x682.jpg" alt="USGS personnel surveying the bathymetry offshore of Crissy Field in San Francisco, California, in 2008. They are using the Coastal Profiling Systemâpersonal watercraft mounted with echo sounders and kinematic Global Positioning System (GPS) units. The Golden Gate Bridge is in the background USGS photograph by Tom Reiss. " width="368" height="245" /></a> USGS personnel surveying the bathymetry offshore of Crissy Field in San Francisco, California, in 2008. They are using the Coastal Profiling Systemâpersonal watercraft mounted with echo sounders and kinematic Global Positioning System (GPS) units. The Golden Gate Bridge is in the background<br />USGS photograph by Tom Reiss.[/caption]

In the San Francisco Bay Areaâan estuarine region defined by its bay, rivers, delta and coastâsediment plays a particularly major role. Sediment helps shape the Bay Areaâs quality of life, from its water quality to its coastal beaches to the ongoing restoration of its tidal wetlands. Dams, dredging and a legacy of hydraulic mining have left their marks on the Bay Areaâs system of âsediment transportââthe scientific term for the water-borne movement of sediment from place to placeâmaking <a href="http://walrus.wr.usgs.gov/coastal_processes/sfbsm/">U.S. Geological Survey</a> science crucial to charting the potential impacts of future human interventions. Yet the Bay Areaâs complex sediment-transport processes have never before been comprehensively studied on a regional scale.

The first ever compilation of research focused on sediment transport in the San Francisco Bay coastal system was published in November as a special issue of the journal <em>Marine Geology</em>, edited by USGS scientists. The volumeâs 21 papers from USGS and other research scientists investigate this complex and ever-changing system through the lenses of hydrology, chemistry, ecology and many other disciplines. The authors characterize how water-borne sand and mud affect not just local landforms and hydrology but also environments hundreds of miles away, through the Golden Gate to the Pacific Ocean and beyond. The research will help planners manage resources of benefit to more than 25 million Californians.

âThe interaction of natural and anthropogenic drivers of sediment transport is highly complex in this heavily urbanized region, and understanding it is critical to the efficient management of sediment resources that affect beaches, tidal-wetland restoration, and sensitive ecosystems throughout the region,â said Patrick Barnard, USGS coastal geologist and managing guest editor of the special issue. âWe hope that this special issue will be instrumental in guiding management decisions for years to come.â

<strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">A History of Sediment</span></strong>

[caption id="attachment_188461" align="alignright" width="367"]<a href="http://www.usgs.gov/blogs/features/files/2014/01/Sed1F1StudyArea1.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-188461  " title="Sed1F1StudyArea" src="http://www.usgs.gov/blogs/features/files/2014/01/Sed1F1StudyArea1.jpg" alt="The San Francisco Bay Coastal System, including major tributaries. Fault lines from Quaternary Fault and Fold Database of the United States. ALI = Alcatraz Island, ANI = Angel Island, BFI = Bay Farm Island, OB = Ocean Beach, TI = Treasure Island, YBI = Yerba Buena Island. Source: Figure 1 of âSediment transport in the San Francisco Bay Coastal System: An overview,â by Patrick L. Barnard, David H. Schoellhamer, Bruce E. Jaffe, and Lester J. McKee, in the Marine Geology special issue (volume 345) released November 2013." width="367" height="282" /></a> The San Francisco Bay Coastal System, including major tributaries. Fault lines from Quaternary Fault and Fold Database of the United States. ALI = Alcatraz Island, ANI = Angel Island, BFI = Bay Farm Island, OB = Ocean Beach, TI = Treasure Island, YBI = Yerba Buena Island.<br />Source: Figure 1 of âSediment transport in the San Francisco Bay Coastal System: An overview,â by Patrick L. Barnard, David H. Schoellhamer, Bruce E. Jaffe, and Lester J. McKee, in the Marine Geology special issue (volume 345) released November 2013.[/caption]

In the late 19th century, the high-pressure jets of water used for hydraulic gold mining pulverized large swaths of the Sierra Nevada foothills and sent trillions of cubic feet of gravel, sand, and mud 150 miles downstream into San Francisco Bay and then into the Pacific Ocean. The sediment changed local landforms by building out Bay shorelines and tidal wetlands, accreting river channels, and adding to the huge, submerged sand bar outside the Golden Gate. This gigantic sediment pulse has taken more than a century to flow through the system. Now that the Gold Rush sediment is on its way out and the water is clearer, scientists are evaluating how the Bay Areaâs natural processes and quality of life will change.

<strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Biological Effects</span></strong>

Sediment influences how hospitable water is to certain organisms. Sediment-laden waters are preferred by some wildlife species, notably the endangered Delta Smelt. In the Bay Area, sediment suspended in bay and delta water has also performed the function of making the water less prone to algal blooms. As the waterâs sediment content has declined in the last couple of decades, its algae count has risen. This phenomenon has been most pronounced in El NiÃ±o years of heavy rain. Discharges or diversions of water from various parts of Californiaâs complex water-resources infrastructure can also affect thisÂ sensitive balance.

[caption id="attachment_188471" align="alignleft" width="384"]<a href="http://www.usgs.gov/blogs/features/files/2014/01/X-60072.jpg"><img class="wp-image-188471 " title="X-60072" src="http://www.usgs.gov/blogs/features/files/2014/01/X-60072.jpg" alt="Gold miners excavating an eroded bluff with jets of water at a placer mine in Dutch Flat, California, between 1857 and 1870. Public domain image Source: &lt;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:X-60072.jpg&gt;." width="384" height="286" /></a> Gold miners excavating an eroded bluff with jets of water at a placer mine in Dutch Flat, California, between 1857 and 1870. Public domain image<br />Source: &lt;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:X-60072.jpg&gt;.[/caption]

To understand the ever-shifting water and sediment dynamics of the San Francisco Bay and delta, and to help managers plan, the USGS deployed automated instruments that have continually measured suspended-sediment concentration, temperature, salinity, and water level at many sites throughout the bay and delta since the 1980s, producing the longest continuous estuarine water-quality data set in history and a model for water-quality monitoring programs throughout the world.

âThe USGS data set is a cornerstone of our federal, state, and local agency collaborative monitoring program,â said Thomas Mumley, Assistant Executive Officer of Californiaâs <a href="http://www.waterboards.ca.gov/rwqcb2/">San Francisco Bay Regional Water Quality Control Board</a>. âIt continues to inform major management actions and decisions on water-quality control, dredging, and habitat restoration.â

